<Docs title="Providers" description="Provider authentication modes, allowed usage, and subscription restrictions.">
  <h1>Providers</h1>
  <p>
    Omegon treats provider authentication as a usage boundary, not just a login choice. Some
    providers are fully unrestricted, some are API-key only, and Anthropic subscription auth is
    interactive-only.
  </p>

  <h2>Current provider auth modes</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Provider / mode</th>
        <th>Configure</th>
        <th>Allowed</th>
        <th>Restrictions</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Anthropic API key</strong></td>
        <td><code>export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY="sk-ant-..."</code></td>
        <td>All Omegon entry points, including TUI, prompts, smoke, and cleave.</td>
        <td>Subject to Anthropic API terms, quota, and model limits.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Anthropic OAuth / subscription</strong></td>
        <td><code>omegon login anthropic</code> or <code>/login anthropic</code></td>
        <td>Interactive TUI sessions only. <code>--initial-prompt</code> is allowed because the session remains human-attended.</td>
        <td><code>--prompt</code>, <code>--prompt-file</code>, <code>--smoke</code>, and <code>/cleave</code> are blocked.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>OpenAI API key</strong></td>
        <td><code>export OPENAI_API_KEY="sk-..."</code></td>
        <td>All supported Omegon entry points.</td>
        <td>Subject to OpenAI billing, quota, and model limits.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Codex OAuth</strong></td>
        <td><code>omegon login openai-codex</code> or <code>/login openai-codex</code></td>
        <td>Supported Codex flows in Omegon.</td>
        <td>No Omegon-specific automation restriction like Anthropic subscription auth.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Ollama</strong></td>
        <td><code>export OLLAMA_HOST="http://127.0.0.1:11434"</code></td>
        <td>All supported local-model workflows.</td>
        <td>Local inference only; no external account auth.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>GitHub Models</strong> <em>(coming soon)</em></td>
        <td>Official PAT configuration will be documented when the integration ships.</td>
        <td>Planned support.</td>
        <td>Not available yet.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Copilot seat</strong> <em>(coming soon)</em></td>
        <td>Seat-based auth will be documented when the integration ships.</td>
        <td>Planned support.</td>
        <td>Not available yet.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Anthropic subscription boundary</h2>
  <p>
    Anthropic subscription auth is the only mode above with a hard interactive-only boundary.
    Omegon blocks automated entry points there because Anthropic's Consumer Terms prohibit
    automated or non-human access unless you are using an Anthropic API key or have explicit
    permission.
  </p>
  <p>
    The consumer terms page is here:
    <a href="https://www.anthropic.com/legal/consumer-terms">anthropic.com/legal/consumer-terms</a>
  </p>

  <h2>Practical guidance</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>If you want to work in the TUI by hand, Anthropic OAuth/subscription is fine.</li>
    <li>If you want prompts, smoke tests, cleave, or other background automation, configure <code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code>.</li>
    <li>If you want local-only inference, use Ollama.</li>
    <li>If you want a provider with no subscription-style automation restriction, use an API-key-based mode.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How this fits the rest of Omegon</h2>
  <p>
    The provider layer feeds the TUI, slash commands, smoke paths, and cleave orchestration. That
    means auth mode affects not just model access, but which entry points Omegon can safely expose.
  </p>
  <p>
    The Anthropic subscription rule is enforced separately in the runtime and disclosed here so the
    operator can choose the right credential before starting work.
  </p>
</Docs>